Author-Name:    Krugman, Paul
Title:   Increasing Returns and Economic Geography. 
Journal: Journal of Political Economy
Pages: 483-99
Issue: 3
Volume: 99
Year: 1991
Month:  June 
Abstract:
  This paper develops a simple model that shows how a country can
 endogenously become differentiated into an industrialized "core" and an
 agricultural "periphery." In order to realize scale economies while
 minimizing transport costs, manufacturing firms tend to locate in the
 region with larger demand, but the location of demand itself depends on
 the distribution of manufacturing. Emergence of a core-periphery pattern
 depends on transportations costs, economies of scale, and the share of
 manufacturing in national income.  Copyright 1991 by University of Chicago Press.
