Author-Name:  Woodland, Linda M
Title:   The Effects of Risk Aversion on Wagering: Point Spread versus Odds. 
Journal: Journal of Political Economy
Pages: 638-53
Issue: 3
Volume: 99
Year: 1991
Month:  June 
Abstract:
  Currently, casinos and bookies use the point-spread method for betting on
 football games. Since an odds system is used in various other sports, what
 factors explain the current structure of the betting market? As the
 bookie's profits are a percentage of the total money wagered, the
 existence of point-spread betting indicates that the total money wagered
 under this betting scheme is greater than that generated by odds betting.
 This paper suggests that the current market structure is a consequence of
 risk-averse attitudes of bettors.  Copyright 1991 by University of Chicago Press.
